## v1.0.0 → v1.1.0 (2026-05-26)

- **changed-by**: ProjectOdyssey PR #5466 — byte-pointer batch-copy bug
- **verification**: verified-ci

### What changed

- Added Pattern 8: byte-pointer arithmetic on dtype-wider tensors silently copies 1 byte per element
- Added 3 new rows to the Failed Attempts table (symmetric-init misdirection, "same code = same correctness" assumption, trusting downstream accessors to surface raw-byte corruption)
- Added Results & Parameters snippet showing wrong vs right batch-copy and a sentinel-based diagnostic
- Added Verified On row for ProjectOdyssey PR #5466
- Bumped version 1.0.0 → 1.1.0 and date to 2026-05-26
- Extended frontmatter `description` to mention the byte-pointer/dtype-width pattern

### Why

A silent-correctness bug surfaced in ProjectOdyssey PR #5466 (fix), originating from PR #5462
(broken example) and #5457 (substrate, vindicated). The LeNet/EMNIST example used
byte-pointer arithmetic on `AnyTensor._data` (`UnsafePointer[UInt8]`) to copy a batch:
`(batch_images._data + dst_idx).store((train_images._data + src_idx).load())`. Because
`load()` on a `UInt8*` returns one byte regardless of the tensor's actual dtype, only N
bytes (1/4 of the float32 storage) were ever written across N iterations; the remaining
3N bytes stayed at `zeros()`. Manual SGD training still converged to 74% test accuracy
because the quantized data retained enough class signal; autograd training was more
sensitive and asymptoted to chance (loss ≈ ln(47) = 3.85, accuracy ≈ 2.76%). The fix is
to use the dtype-agnostic accessors `_set_float64`/`_get_float64` which round-trip through
Float64 at the tensor's actual precision. Post-fix the autograd 5-epoch run reproduces
the manual baseline bit-for-bit on epoch 1 (46.70%) and tracks within 0.15 pp through
epoch 5 (74.24% vs 74.39%). This is a NEW class of silent tensor-numeric-correctness bug
(byte-pointer vs dtype-pointer arithmetic) distinct from the existing 7 patterns, so it
warrants a Minor version bump rather than a Patch.

